Dowager Empress Maria Feodorovna of Russia with nurses outside a hospital, Russia, 1916

Dowager Empress Maria Feodorovna of Russia with nurses outside a hospital, Russia, 1916. Born Princess Dagmar of Denmark, Maria Feodorovna (1847-1928) married the future Tsar Alexander III in 1866. Alexander died in 1894. During the First World War, Maria Feodorovna supervised hospitals in Kiev. She is pictured here before the Hospital of Grand Duchess Olga Alexandrovna of Russia. Found in the collection of the Russian State Film and Photo Archive, Krasnogorsk

EDITORS COMMENTS

This print captures Dowager Empress Maria Feodorovna of Russia standing proudly with a group of nurses outside a hospital in Russia, circa 1916. Born Princess Dagmar of Denmark, Maria Feodorovna was married to Tsar Alexander III in 1866 until his death in 1894. During the tumultuous years of the First World War, she took charge of supervising hospitals in Kiev. In this poignant image, we see her before the Hospital of Grand Duchess Olga Alexandrovna of Russia. The empress exudes grace and strength as she stands tall alongside these dedicated healthcare professionals. The monochrome composition adds a timeless quality to the scene, emphasizing the historical significance. Maria Feodorovna's commitment to serving her country during wartime is evident here. Her presence symbolizes not only her dedication to improving medical care but also her unwavering support for those affected by conflict. As part of the Romanov dynasty, Maria Feodorovna played an important role on the home front during World War I. This photograph serves as a testament to her leadership and compassion amidst challenging circumstances. Preserved within the collection of the Russian State Film and Photo Archive in Krasnogorsk, this image offers us a glimpse into an era gone by—a reminder that even during times of war, acts of kindness and healing can shine through.
